From: knsol <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH] fix: don't kill SD writes whenever any BLE client is connected

Found 2026-05-03 after patch 0031 (fs_sync) didn't fix the symptom of
get_file_size("audio/a01.txt") == 0 forever during recording.

Root cause is upstream of write_to_file: the pusher() loop in
transport.c gates SD writes on `!storage_is_on`, but `storage_is_on`
gets set to true on EVERY BLE connection — not only when a client is
actively pulling files from the omi storage service.

Two offending sites, both originally written for omi's mobile app
which always reads storage:

  1. transport.c:403 (_transport_connected): unconditional
     `storage_is_on = true` on every BLE connect, regardless of
     intent. mobile_app.py / nRF Connect / any test BLE client trips
     this and kills SD writes for the entire connection lifetime.

  2. storage.c:88 (storage_config_changed_handler): sets
     `storage_is_on = true` BEFORE the if/else that distinguishes
     subscribe vs unsubscribe — so even an unsubscribe sets it true.

Fix:

  - Remove the unconditional set in _transport_connected. The
    disconnect callback already clears it.
  - Make storage_config_changed_handler set `storage_is_on` to
    `(value == BT_GATT_CCC_NOTIFY)` so it tracks subscription state
    correctly.

Effect: SD writes happen during ordinary BLE connections (live
streaming, info read, etc.). They're only paused while a client is
actually subscribed to the omi storage notify char, which is the
intended behaviour for serving file downloads.
---
diff --git a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c
--- a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c
+++ b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c
@@ -400,7 +400,11 @@ static void _transport_connected(struct bt_conn *conn, uint8_t err)
 static void _transport_connected(struct bt_conn *conn, uint8_t err)
 {
     struct bt_conn_info info = {0};
-    storage_is_on = true;
+    /* Patch 0032: do NOT force storage_is_on=true on every connect.
+     * That was killing SD writes for the entire connection lifetime
+     * even when the client never touched the storage service. The
+     * subscription state of the storage notify char is the correct
+     * signal; storage_config_changed_handler maintains that. */

     err = bt_conn_get_info(conn, &info);
     if (err) {
diff --git a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/storage.c b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/storage.c
--- a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/storage.c
+++ b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/storage.c
@@ -85,7 +85,8 @@ static void storage_config_changed_handler(const struct bt_gatt_attr *attr, uint
 static void storage_config_changed_handler(const struct bt_gatt_attr *attr, uint16_t value)
 {

-    storage_is_on = true;
+    /* Patch 0032: track subscribe vs unsubscribe accurately. */
+    storage_is_on = (value == BT_GATT_CCC_NOTIFY);
     if (value == BT_GATT_CCC_NOTIFY) {
         LOG_INF("Client subscribed for notifications");
     } else if (value == 0) {
